{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b481e584-aaf3-4fe4-9bb3-a5023a281111","content":"The template is **functional but not fully publish-ready**. Here's my assessment:\n\n**✅ Present & correct:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author` — all set\n- `sourceName` for name substitution\n- `classifications` and `tags` (language + type)\n- `Framework` symbol with choices\n\n**⚠️ Missing / recommended for NuGet:**\n\n| Field | Why it matters |\n|---|---|\n| `$schema` | Enables editor validation (`https://json.schemastore.org/template`) |\n| `description` | Shown on NuGet.org and in `dotnet new search` — critical for discoverability |\n| `groupIdentity` | Groups related templates; recommended for NuGet packages |\n| `preferNameDirectory` | Should be `true` for project templates |\n\n**📦 Packaging gap:** There's no `.csproj` or `.nuspec` to produce a NuGet package. You'll need a pack project (typically a `csproj` with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>`) to actually publish.\n\n**Summary:** Add a `description`, `groupIdentity`, `$schema`, and `preferNameDirectory`, then create a packaging project. After that it's ready to go.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b2c21967-2145-43f7-a20d-dd0060a3ff1a","outputTokens":297},"id":"819feefc-2a46-4364-b476-d982cf9bdc99","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:43:05.241Z","parentId":"8c3d82a9-066e-4654-b37a-e34089753750"}
